{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b5d991ea-7dfd-4db9-aba8-e6d70f3ee33d","content":"\n\n`OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on `Application` in MAUI, so your existing overrides will compile. However, MAUI's recommended approach is **Window-level lifecycle events**:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window override |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped()` / `OnBackgrounding()` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed()` |\n\nOverride `CreateWindow` to return a custom `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n    }\n}\n\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()      { /* was OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped()      { /* was OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()      { /* was OnResume */ }\n    protected override void OnDestroying()   { /* new - app closing */ }\n    protected override void OnActivated()    { /* new - window focused */ }\n    protected override void OnDeactivated()  { /* new - window lost focus */ }\n}\n```\n\nThe `Window` approach gives you finer-grained control (e.g., distinguishing \"backgrounded\" vs \"destroyed\") and works correctly in multi-window scenarios.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3bcc44a7-ed12-4ff2-b6db-d49e43355423","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle events from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed significantly — these methods still exist on `Application` for basic compatibility, but the recommended approach is to use the **Window lifecycle events** or the **cross-platform lifecycle events** via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n\nThe old `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` methods are still available on the `Application` class for backward compatibility, but MAUI introduced a more granular Window-level lifecycle with events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding`. You can either override `CreateWindow` to return a custom `Window` with lifecycle overrides, or hook into these events directly on your window instance.","outputTokens":809},"id":"2001b7f7-1ecd-40b6-a0ec-cc6502759907","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:46:24.302Z","parentId":"e2d519be-95c7-47fd-8902-8064edecf38c"}
